<HEAD>Connecticut Lawyer Sets McKinley Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 71-year-old lawyer has become the oldest climber on record to reach the summit of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> McKinley </LOCATION>, the highest peak in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Middlebury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, reached the top of the 20,320-foot peak Sunday in an unusually fast eight days from <PERSON> Kahiltna </PERSON> <PERSON> Glacier </PERSON>, at <PERSON> McKinley </PERSON>'s 7,000-foot level, rangers said Friday. Records show the oldest climber prior to <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> was 68. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> said he learned of the potential for a mountaineering milestone when he checked in with rangers before the climb. `` So I said, ` Thank you very much,''' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> climbed </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinley </PERSON> with a guide, <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON>, and another mountaineer, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Landry </PERSON>, 24, who suffered altitude sickness and did n't reach the summit until Monday. The three returned to <PERSON> Kahiltna </PERSON> <PERSON> Glacier </PERSON>, and on Wednesday, they flew back to <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>. `` I found it extremely arduous above 14,000 feet,'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> said. `` It's heavy work.''
