<HEAD>Nikkei Rises Slightly After Worst Trading Week This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The main market barometer recouped early losses by the close of half-day trading Saturday, but still finished lower at the end of its worst trading week so far this year. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a sharp 391.13-point loser Friday, lost nearly 80 points shortly after trading started, but claimed back lost ground to close the day at 27,301.34 points, up 16.33 points, or 0.059 percent. `` The index moved up mainly on profit-taking,'' said <PERSON> Michio </PERSON> <PERSON> Katsumata </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest brokerage. `` <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> and IC-related companies moved higher up,'' but otherwise `` the market was very quiet,'' the spokesman added. Shares from <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION>, a leading consumer electronics maker, closed at a historic high 6,460 yen, up 430 yen, surpassing its previous record close reached Friday. Volume on the first section during the half-day session totaled 600 million shares. Despite Saturday's slight gain, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index closed the week down 612.45 points, or 2.19 percent, from a 27,913.79-point close July 15. It had lost 513.09 points during Tuesday trading alone. `` People are anxious about higher interest rates,'' said <PERSON> Katsumata </PERSON>. Banks in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have all raised their rates, `` but only <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is sticking to a lower rate,'' he added. The market next week will just move `` up and down, up and down,'' the spokesman predicted. The foreign exchange market is closed on Saturdays.
