<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fire Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAIL ROAD FLAT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They live by a brutal code of each man for himself in prison, but in the middle of the woods they learn to stand together against a fiery enemy that is not affected by their crimes, color or gangs. `` We ca n't bring our problems with us to the fire lines,'' said <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rojas </PERSON>, 20, of <PERSON> Hollister </PERSON>, who is serving time in the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Youth Authority for burglary. <PERSON> Rojas </PERSON> was among hundreds of state prisoners battling a pair of arson-linked wildfires in heavy timber and brush near the <LOCATION> Calaveras </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Rail </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Flat </LOCATION>, 150 miles east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> on Friday offered a $ 10,000 reward for the capture of the arsonist and declared a state of emergency in the county. Nearly 11,000 acres and six homes had been charred by Friday as firefighters neared containment of the blazes, which have caused an estimated $ 3.8 million damage to the drought-parched region since Tuesday. Wielding shovels, saws and other hand tools, state fire Capt. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Segura </PERSON>'s strike team of inmates stood guard Thursday when the fire burned out to a section of the more than 18 miles of bare-earth control lines that firefighters had carved around the fires. `` Let it burn right to the edge,'' <PERSON> Segura </PERSON> bellowed at the inmates, clad in orange jumpsuits. Some of the inmates had to use ladders off a nearby state pumper truck to climb up the near-vertical mountain toward the advancing flames. Within minutes, he told his crew from the <ORGANIZATION> DeWitt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nelson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> CYA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Camp </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Stockton </LOCATION> that it seemed the line would hold for the time being. A few of the inmates slid down the slope hand over hand on a fire hose. Others descended on the ladder. Hours after being dumped off from a stifling personnel truck, it was finally break time. `` This is better than being behind walls,'' <PERSON> Rojas </PERSON> said in an idle moment. Added team member <PERSON> Stevie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>: `` Every time they ask, ` You want to go on a fire?' everybody stands up and says ` Yeah.''' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, 19, of <LOCATION> Vallejo </LOCATION>, is serving a sentence for possession of cocaine. Inmates in the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Youth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Authority </LOCATION> or state prison systems can volunteer to train as firefighters, but candidates are screened to determine that they are suited and that they are low security risks. Supervisors are unarmed, but even so there are very few escape attempts. Correctional officer <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON>, supervising state prisoners in line for food at the Rail Road Flat fire camp after coming off the lines, said most of the inmate firefighters are proud of what they do. `` They like getting outside and later you hear them say things like ` Hey, we saved a house there,''' <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> said. Added prisoner <PERSON> Myron </PERSON> <PERSON> Bright </PERSON>, with a sincere expression on his face: `` It's a good way to pay my debt to society.'' Bright, 36, who is serving time for insurance fraud, works out of the <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> camp near Folsom Prison. <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> said he and other crew supervisors make allowances because of the nature of the work. `` If you're out there for more than a week at a time, they get antsy. If you're real strict, they wo n't respond in a good way, and you do n't need tension on a fire,'' he said. The inmates said they realize the work is dangerous, but trust the supervisors to keep them alive. One prisoner said the work has changed the direction of his life. `` I'd like to become a professional firefighter,'' said <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. `` The first week I get out, I'm going to put in an application somewhere.''
