<SECOND>AM-Food Poisoning,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contaminated Hose Blamed For Academy Food-Poisoning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A contaminated water hose in the kitchen of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION>'s cadet dining hall apparently caused the outbreak of food poisoning that affected 673 people, academy officials said Friday. Officials said a floor drain had backed up in the kitchen of <ORGANIZATION> Mitchell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> on July 12, and the hose was placed in the drain in an effort to clear it. The hose then was used to rinse celery that was put in the chicken salad served at lunch that day. Bacteriological tests shows the hose was contaminated with E. coli bacteria. Tests were still being conducted on the food to confirm that the bacteria in the hose caused the outbreak of gastroenteritis. Academy officials said they planned to have civil engineers examine the 30-year-old drain system. They also said they planned to review kitchen procedures, including how food handlers are trained and supervised.
