<HEAD>Justice Finds No Basis to Investigate Former Deputy Attorney
General Burns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has found no basis to investigate former Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> for promoting a former law partner for a judgeship, sources say. The criminal division's public integrity section reached the conclusion after reviewing information about the relationship between <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Summit </PERSON>, who has been nominated to the 2nd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, according to the sources, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> and former criminal division chief <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> plan to testify before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday about their March 29 protest resignations. They quit out of concern that the continued tenure of Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> was hurting <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> operations and morale. The <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Times disclosed <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>' support for Summit last month, suggesting the former deputy attorney general might have violated federal conflict-of-interest law. The <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Times this month disclosed that <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> had been the focus of an internal <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigation into whether he smoked marijuana at a wedding in 1982. <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> has emphatically denied the allegation, made in an anonymous letter, and the department's Office of Professional Responsibility closed the matter. Congressional sources and sources close to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> have said the leaking of unfavorable information about <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> and <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> has been an attempt to discourage them from testifying before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> was still receiving payments from the law firm and had investments in limited partnerships with Summit at the time he was urging Summit's nomination last year. When asked Friday about the public integrity section's decision, <PERSON> Summit </PERSON> said he was `` not surprised, there never was anything to it'' and said he was pleased about the outcome.
