<HEAD>Shultz Helps Israel Settle Soviet Jews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> has decided to help <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> hold on to Soviet Jews who might prefer settling in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. He will not oppose a prospective change in Israeli procedures designed to stem the exodus to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of Jews who left the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> with exit permits for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, the officials said Friday. But <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> is likely to heed the advice of the bureaus that handle Soviet and refugee affairs and keep pushing <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to permit wider emigration across the board. Most Jews who leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are permitted to depart if they can get visas from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Once they reach <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, the transit point for Soviet emigres, nearly 90 percent of them go elsewhere, mostly to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and are taken in by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as refugees. Concerned about the situation, the Israeli Cabinet has ordered a change in procedures. Soviet Jews granted exit permits would receive their Israeli visas in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and fly to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The change in procedure, which has not been put into effect, would make it harder for Soviet Jews to come to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because they would have to qualify for entry as immigrants. This could require long waiting periods and most would be fenced out for various reasons as ineligible. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s European bureau, which is involved in Soviet policy, and the <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> had both recommended to <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> that he urge <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to change its policy and appeal to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to permit wider emigration. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schifter </PERSON>, the assistant secretary of <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanitarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, proposed that Soviet Jews remain eligible for admission to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as refugees even after they reach <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Near Eastern bureau, which deals in Arab and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> affairs, recommended to <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> that he not contest the Israeli Cabinet's decision _ advice he will follow, at least temporarily, according to officials who spoke on the condition they not be identified. `` The debate is less a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> debate than a debate about feeling the Israelis would be insulted and that it would undermine the purpose of the State of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> if refugees left the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and did not go to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' an official said. `` They need and want immigrants.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> representative of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, described the problem as `` one of the hottest and most complex issues in <LOCATION> Israeli-Diaspora </LOCATION> debate.'' He referred to divergent views among Jews living in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and elsewhere around the world. `` Ideally,'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said, `` the compromise would be a two-track policy. Soviet Jews who want to go to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would leave the <LOCATION> U.S.S.R. </LOCATION> with Israeli visas. Those seeking resettlement in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would leave with American visas. It is our hope the administration will press the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> in this direction. It's fair, it's equitable, its logical.'' Most Soviet citizens are unable to obtain exit permits. But thousands of Jews, Armenians and ethnic Germans over the years have enjoyed a special privilege of emigrating. Very small numbers of Jews are permitted to go directly to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The others can leave only if they obtain visas for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.
