opposition leader, said Wednesday his party is ready to sign the agreement. `` <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> is demanding that both political parties work together to bring the madness of political violence to an end,'' he said. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Golding </PERSON>, chairman of the governing party, said the parties must have the political will to end the violence before signing a peace pact. Groups signing the statement included the <ORGANIZATION> Jamaica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tourist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Employers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> and the Exporters Association of <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>.
