<HEAD>Five Poisoned In Chemical Mix-Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A chemical company in eastern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> mistakenly sold a restaurant a lethal chemical compound instead of baking soda, and five diners died of poisoning and 140 others became ill, a newspaper reported today. The Peasant Daily said the people were poisoned June 23 after a chemical company in <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION> province sold the restaurant sodium fluosilicate rather than sodium bicarbonate, or baking soda. Sodium fluosilicate is used in insecticides and ceramics. Customers who bought the restaurant's buns containing the poisonous chemical suffered from serious stomach pains, vomiting and diarrhea, the report said. It said the person in charge of the warehouse at the chemical company was arrested after being found responsible for the mistake.
