8th pvs, `Residents in...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s government-controlled radio said hundreds of pilgrims Friday protested the deaths last year of 402 people and that police attacked some of the protesters. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> on Saturday denied the report as `` lies and fabrications,'' and area residents contacted by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> said they had heard no reports of violence. Parts of the report by <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio, monitored in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, were indistinct, but monitors said they did not hear any reference to injuries. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> said more than 1 million pilgrims from around the world gathered Friday in 111-degree temperatures for Sabbath prayers at the Grand Mosque in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, which houses Islam's holiest shrine. The pilgrims, who came from more than 130 countries, have converged on Mecca for the annual hajj rituals, one of the five sacraments that any able Moslem is required to perform once a lifetime. Government-run Saudi radio quoted an unidentified official source as saying the Iranian report, along with a similar Iranian report on Wednesday, was `` made up.'' The source said it was one of a series of `` lies and fabrications'' broadcast by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to create tension. He said pilgrims in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> were undertaking their rites `` in calm and secure conditions.'' Residents in the <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> area reached by telephone from <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> said they were not aware of any violence. They said pilgrims prayed early Saturday in preparation for the culmination of the pilgrimage. Other residents reached in <LOCATION> Jiddah </LOCATION> also said they had heard no reports of violence. `` Hundreds of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Turk </LOCATION>, Afghan, Pakistani and American pilgrims demonstrated in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> today -LRB- Friday -RRB-, chanting slogans ... and carrying placards condemning the <PERSON> Al-Saud </PERSON> regime in their killing of over 400 pilgrims of the holy sanctuary last year in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>,'' <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio said. It added: `` According to received reports, the Saudi regime's police ... subjected the demonstrators to severe control and surrounded them In some sections, they attacked the ranks of the marchers.'' During last year's pilgrimage to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, 25 miles east of <LOCATION> Jiddah </LOCATION>, 402 people were killed in riots. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> said the pilgrims, 275 of them Iranians, died in a stampede. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> claimed Saudi police shot them. The Saudis accused the Iranians of holding demonstrations, including anti-U.S. protests, in defiance of a ban on political activity. Last April, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> broke off diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, citing terrorism and subversion. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> has been receiving the pilgrims and organizing the hajj this year with extensive security measures to prevent a recurrence of last year's violence. The official <ORGANIZATION> Saudi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said thousands of worshipers gathered inside the Grand Mosque Friday, in its expansive courtyard or on its roof. The roof alone has a capacity of 80,000 people, the agency said. After the Friday prayers at the mosque, which harbors the <LOCATION> Kaaba </LOCATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s most sacred shrine _ the worshipers moved three miles away to <PERSON> Mina </PERSON>. Pilgrims spend the rest of the day in <LOCATION> Mina </LOCATION> praying in preparation for the culmination of hajj on Saturday. The agency reported the temperature in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, 25 miles east of <LOCATION> Jiddah </LOCATION>, was 111 degrees. <LOCATION> Jiddah </LOCATION> is the kingdom's capital. Saturday, the ninth day of the month of Zhul-Hijja by Islamic calendar, is earmarked as `` Wukuf,'' or the day of standing, when pilgrims wake at dawn and travel another six miles to <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, where they remain praying, chanting and listening to sermons. Saturday night is spent at <LOCATION> Muzdalifa </LOCATION>, about four miles away, where pebbles are thrown in a ritual stoning of the devil. At dawn Sunday, sheep are slaughtered in sacrifice and the hajj ends for the hundreds of thousands who have come by air, sea and land. A four-day Eid al-Adha or Feast of Sacrifice, then follows throughout the Moslem world. It is the biggest religious congregation on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, and reports from <PERSON> Mecca </PERSON> said traffic was moving smoothly but slowly Friday. Thousands of vehicles, mainly buses, coasters and jeeps were used to transport the pilgrims, although thousands preferred to move on foot, according to the reports. The director general of passports administration, Gen. <PERSON> Fahd </PERSON> <PERSON> bin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Sherif </PERSON>, told the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> news agency that 762,755 pilgrims arrived from abroad as of Monday. The foreigners, who included Moslem heads of state, premiers and ministers, joined about half a million more from within <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. These include worshipers and thousands who come to provide services, including about 20,000 security men, according to diplomatic sources. The Iranians boycotted this year's pilgrimage when <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> sought to reduce the numbers f pilgrims, citing massive renovations at <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> and neighboring <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>, which harbors the tomb of the prophet <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>. Pilgrims visit <PERSON> Medina </PERSON> after the hajj formally ends. Iranians have urged other Moslems to take control of Mecca from the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> rulers, who are its custodians. Iranian television reported demonstrations took place but Saudi authorities denied that.
