<HEAD>Iraqis Wary of Celebrating War's End</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Weddings and soccer games still stir Iraqis' Arab zeal for celebration, and a religious holiday can be a time of great feasting. But Iraqis are showing an uncharacteristic lack of jubilation over <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s agreement to halt its 8-year-old war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. For people like <PERSON> Suad </PERSON> <PERSON> Mousa </PERSON>, the war will end only when her family is reunited. `` I really want the guns to fall silent and for my dear husband to come home,'' said the 34-year-old mother of three, whose husband has been in the army since the war began. `` When the Iranians said they would accept the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- cease-fire -RRB- resolution, I really thought the war was finally over, but it seems now it will take weeks and probably months before he will be back,'' she said. Such war-weary wariness has been common in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> after <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> agreed Monday to accept a truce. `` There was nothing. No reaction,'' said a European diplomat who was in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> on Monday. Iraqis seem deeply suspicious of the Iranian decision, and the government is insisting any truce be tied to a final settlement. Parades, celebrations and television specials typically greet Iraqi victories in battle. None followed the Iranian announcement. Official news media and President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s ruling <ORGANIZATION> Baath </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> have encouraged caution and continued vigilance by the military. The army has continued to fight, and it said Thursday night it had recaptured 33 northern hills lost to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in the early days of the war. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said Iraqi units penetrated 12 miles into its territory Friday and claimed <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used chemical weapons. Exultation is common here over much less than the end of a long and costly war. Fusillades of tracer bullets lit the night sky over <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> when <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> defeated rival <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> in the Arab soccer championship Thursday night. Wedding parties toot car horns and bang drums as they move through the streets of <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>. Families are buying sheep to slaughter for the Eid al-Adha feast that marks the end of <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s season of pilgrimage to Mecca. The date depends on the moon, but it is expected Sunday or Monday. Celebration of the war's end, however, apparently will have to wait for a final peace. Diplomats in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> say distrust of the Iranians, who accepted a <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution they had rejected since its passage a year ago, is rooted in hundreds of years of conflict between <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Government officials also feel <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> may want a truce only as a respite in which to rebuild their army, which has lost several battles this year. Some cite Iranian statements that a cease-fire does not mean the end of the war, which <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s revolutionary patriarch <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> sees as a crusade for his own vision of Islam. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> rejected proposals of a cease-fire two years ago when its own forces were being battered near the southern city of <LOCATION> Basra </LOCATION> and many observers felt collapse was near. It would `` certainly not'' accept a truce without real peace now that it has the upper hand militarily, said a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat who recently talked with Iraqi officials. He said <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> insists on direct peace talks with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> as a sign `` of serious purpose.'' A European diplomat said Iraqis are `` still going to be nervous about the Iranians because the Iranians have n't been beaten'' and still are ruled by crusading clerics. He said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> `` could be militarily quite potent ... within a year or two.'' Although they are not celebrating, ordinary Iraqis are anxious for the war to end. `` I am an old man,'' said 68-year-old <PERSON> Mahmoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaker </PERSON> at the counter of his auto parts store. `` I have been running the shop for four years, since my elder son was conscripted. I am very tired and I want him back to the shop and with the family.''
