<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has developed a plan that would give each nation unprecedented access to each other's bomber bases, strategic naval ports and military ships as a way of verifying constraints on cruise missiles, according to a report published today. The Washington Post, quoting Soviet officials, reported the proposal calls for permanently stationing teams of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet inspectors outside factories where cruise missiles are produced, where their warheads are installed and where the weapons are loaded onto submarines and other ships. It also calls for periodic inspection of military bases where long-range aircraft are equipped with cruise missiles, and short-notice inspections of unrelated sites where cruise missiles are strongly suspected of being illegally stored. The <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> plan was outlined in interviews with <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s disarmament chief, and Col. Gen. <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Chervov </PERSON>, senior arms control adviser on the Soviet general staff. According to <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chervov </PERSON>, Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> still wants to sign an agreement with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sharply cutting strategic offensive nuclear arms and incorporating these inspection rights to verify each side's compliance. But the Soviet officials said the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration thus far has blocked the plan because of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> resistance to proposed Soviet inspections. They called on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to `` make a political decision'' in 