he rightist, pro-American Somoza dynasty that ruled <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> for 42 years until the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> overthrew it in 1979. His background is a source of suspicion for some members of the resistance who fear the rebel movement is turning to the right. The controversy heated up after <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> was elected to the directorate Monday in the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>. The seven commanders of the small Contra organization called the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, which has a political base in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, resigned in protest. <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> was the top military commander of the main, Honduras-based Contra force. <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> publicly appealed to the seven Friday to withdraw their resignations. He said the new directorate `` will delegate areas of responsibility and, in this sense, Col. <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> will step down next week from the general command of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> said the leaders who resigned were frustrated that they were not getting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid. He said the Costa Rican government would not allow delivery through <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>. The Contra force led by <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> got <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid through <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> said the Contras asked <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> two months ago for permission to deliver humanitarian aid through the Costa Rican <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, but have received no reply. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> cut off military aid to the Contras in February.
