<SECOND>PM-Confidentiality Verdict,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Rules Against Newspapers in Confidentiality Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLAYTON HASWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury verdict awarding $ 700,000 in damages to a confidential source whose name was revealed by two newspapers could open the door to scores of similar lawsuits, a First Amendment expert says. The <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> were ordered Friday to pay $ 200,000 in actual damages and $ 250,000 each in punitive damages to <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> for a 1982 story that named him as the source of information about a political candidate's shoplifting conviction years earlier. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said reporters had promised him anonymity. The jury decided that a promise of confidentiality was an oral contract. `` It's very important to keep your word,'' a tearful <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said after the verdict. `` That's the hard currency of journalism. That's the hard currency of politics When that currency is devalued, we all suffer.'' The verdict distressed journalists, who have faced contempt charges and jail for not revealing sources, and now could face damages if they do. `` I believe this is absolutely unprecedented,'' said <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City-based </LOCATION> attorney who has represented <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and other media organizations. `` If not reversed, this decision opens the door for an enormous range of real or imagined sources to claim that, in one way or another, they've been victimized by the press,'' <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Finnegan </PERSON>, senior vice president-assistant publisher for the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dispatch </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON>, managing editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>, said an appeal is likely of the <LOCATION> Hennepin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> jury's 5-1 verdict. `` What we've been saying is disclosure of an 11th-hour dirty trick was at least as important as the 12-year-old shoplifting record which <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> was revealing,'' <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Finnegan </PERSON> said the punitive damages, associated with a finding of fraud and misrepresentation, `` ignores the fact that the editors involved handled the story honestly, fairly and accurately.'' `` In no way did we misrepresent. Nor were we guilty of fraud in our dealings with Mr. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Finnegan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Pruitt </PERSON>, counsel for <ORGANIZATION> McClatchy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, said the verdict was understandable because the judge did not instruct the jury on First Amendment issues. Making a reporter-source relationship a simple contract gives those who want to sue the press a new way to circumvent constitutional protections, <PERSON> Pruitt </PERSON> said. The suit centered on a decision by editors at both newspapers to overrule their reporters and use <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>'s name. At the time, <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> was a spokesman for <PERSON> Wheelock </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON>, an Independent-Republican candidate for governor. Six days before the election, <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> gave reporters documents showing that <PERSON> Marlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic-Farmer-Labor </ORGANIZATION> candidate for lieutenant governor, admitted shoplifting $ 6 in merchandise. The documents were given on condition <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>'s identity not be revealed. The day the stories appeared, <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> was fired from his $ 35,000-a-year job as a public relations executive with an advertising agency, said his attorney, <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothenberg </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> claimed he lost $ 725,000 in wages and pension. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> now has his own public relations firm and made $ 93,000 last year, according to testimony. In a related development, the Star Tribune began recalling all 640,000 copies of this weekend's Sunday Magazine after a person quoted by name in the magazine said she had been promised anonymity. Executive editor <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> that the <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> case `` figured in our thinking, but I'm not saying that's our only reason.'' He said publisher <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Parkinson </PERSON> made the decision after editors concluded they were n't sure whether a pledge of anonymity had been given by the free-lancer who wrote the article.
