<HEAD>Federal Judge Gives Settlement Money to Australia and New Zealand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Representatives of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> were given checks totaling $ 5 million to be distributed to those who were exposed to the herbicide Agent Orange during the Vietnam War. On hand to accept the checks Friday were Australian General Consul <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurford </PERSON> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> General Consul <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cotton </PERSON>. The checks were made out to the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> Agent Orange Trust and the Australian Vietnam War Veterans Trust and were part of a $ 240 million settlement of suits against the chemical's makers. According to figures contained in 1985 court papers, 48,400 troops from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and 3,842 troops from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> served with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> during the war in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. The checks, $ 4.5 million for Australian veterans and $ 500,000 for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, were presented by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, who oversees the Agent Orange litigation. <PERSON> Hurford </PERSON> thanked <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> on behalf of the <LOCATION> Australian </LOCATION> people `` that you have not forgotten the Australian veterans.'' Cotton also expressed his `` deepest appreciation'' and said that `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are happy to be together in peace.'' `` Please express to your veterans our appreciation for the help they gave us and our desire to help them as much as possible, our comrades in arms,'' <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> said during the ceremony in his chambers. The class-action suit, which was filed in 1978, was settled in 1984 when the chemical companies agreed to pay $ 180 million. Interest gained during a lengthy appeal process upped the fund to $ 240 million. The companies sued were <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION>, Uniroyal, Hercules, T.H. Agriculture and Nutrition, <PERSON> Diamond </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. Agent Orange was sprayed over <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> during the 1960s by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military, which hoped to deprive communist troops of crops and cover. The herbicide contains the highly toxic dioxin, and veterans contend that exposure to the defoliant causes cancer and other illnesses. Under a distribution plan, $ 170 million of the fund will be used for cash payments to American veterans, $ 52 million will finance social service projects to help <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans and their families and $ 17 million will pay for attorneys' fees and administrative costs.
