<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Burmese Leader Resigns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thuout with to UPDATE with details, background. ADDS
byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ne Win, who wielded authoritarian power over <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> for 26 years, resigned today as chairman of the country's only political party and called for a referendum on ending one-party rule, sources said. Five other veteran leaders also offered their resignations, according to the sources, who attended a party conference where the announcement was made. The 78-year-old Ne Win cited poor health for his decision, they said. But the dramatic announcement came in wake of bloody student rioting, dawn-to-dusk curfews and a worsening economy. Speaking to an extraordinary session of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON> said a referendum would be held before the end of September to decide whether the nation wanted a multi-party system or a continuation of single-party rule, the sources said. If the congress accepts Ne Win's resignation _ which it is almost certain to do _ party rules call for the election of a new chairman at the same congress. Ne Win resigned from the presidency in 1981 but retained the far more important party post. He was regarded as the most powerful figure in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>. The resignation announcement was made available from people attending the congress, which was closed to foreign media and the public. Ne Win's speech was scheduled for public release later today. Ne Win, who came to power in 1962 military coup, has steered <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> along an isolationist road. His socialist economic policies have proved increasingly ineffective. Dissident viewpoints were quickly silenced. But since October, student-led demonstrations have three times rocked <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> and other <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> cities, resulting in violent deaths, mass arrests and the closure of universities. Ne Win also asked the congress to approve the resignations of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yu </LOCATION>, the party vice chairman and president of the country; <PERSON> Aye </PERSON> <PERSON> Ko </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION> secretary general and vice president; <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>, party joint general secretary and secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Kyaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Htin </PERSON>, member of the party's central executive committee, deputy prime minister and defense minister; and <PERSON> Tun </PERSON> <PERSON> Tin </PERSON>, central executive committee member, deputy prime minister and finance minister. There was speculation that the five would retain their government positions, at least until the referendum is held. About 1,000 delegates are attending the three-day congress which opened earlier today at <LOCATION> Kyaikkasan </LOCATION> grounds. Authorities announced the congress on July 7, two weeks after thousands of students and other demonstrators battled riot police in the streets of the capital, leaving at least nine persons dead. Authorities have lifted a dusk-to-dawn curfew that was imposed on <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> following the rioting, but violence spread to the cities of <LOCATION> Prome </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taunggyi </LOCATION> last week, with at least four people reported killed. Earlier this week the government radio disclosed that 41 people who were packed into police vans during rioting in March suffocated on their way to prison. Min <PERSON> Goung </PERSON> took responsibility for the tragedy, and resigned from his posts as home and religious affairs minister and in the 17-member party Central Executive Committee, the top policy-making body. Despite promises of economic liberalization last year, the government in October withdrew three currency notes from circulation and offered no compensation. This caused the first of the three major anti-government protests. Western diplomats in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> and knowledgeable Western observers said these outbursts, after years of passivity, reflected intense disillusionment with a government that has monopolized power for a quarter century while leading the resource-rich nation into economic ruin. In the past, Ne Win rooted out opponents and dealt harshly with the few occasions of open protest. Rarely seen in public, never interviewed by the press, <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON> is said to be a superb and highly intelligent political in-fighter and strong nationalist. Regarded as potentially the richest nation in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> _ with a per capita income of less than $ 200 _ is among the world's 10 poorest countries. Once the world's largeset rice exporter and oil producer, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> has suffered spot food shortages and has had to import petroleum products recently. Although the state officially controls much of the economy, most Burmese rely on black market goods smuggled in from <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. Foreign analysts and many Burmese blame Ne Win's rigid, so-called `` Burmese Way to Socialism'' for these failures. The system is an amalgam of a centralized economy, one-party military-backed rule and Buddhism. Probably as a result of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s colonial past, <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON> also sought to exclude foreign influence.
</TEXT>
