 A strong earthquake shook western <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> today, the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observatory </ORGANIZATION> reported. The epicenter of the quake, with an estimated reading of 5.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, was 680 miles northwest of the Mongolian capital of <LOCATION> Ulaanbaatar </LOCATION>, according to the observatory. A spokesman said the earthquake was recorded at 3:45 p.m. No other details were available. The Richter scale measures ground motion as recorded on seismographs. An earthquake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage in a populated area.
