<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-CrimeCode     07-23 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Crime Code,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Criminal Code Narrows Use of Death Penalty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An official revision of the Soviet criminal code greatly reduces the number of offenses punishable by death, making execution possible only in cases of premeditated murder, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> reported today. The state-run radio said the proposed revision of the 28-year-old code also frequently replaces imprisonment with fines and other means of punishment. `` The new legislation will be more democratic and humane,'' <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> said, quoting a Soviet professor, <PERSON> Ninel </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuznetsova </PERSON>. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, a lawyer by training, has spearheaded the revision of the Soviet criminal code as part of his effort to rid his country's economy and society of a Stalinist legacy. The current code permits the execution of people convicted of treason, murder, flagrant corruption, war crimes and other offenses. Soviet media occasionally report on executions but have never indicated how frequently the death penalty is invoked. People sentenced to death in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are shot by a firing squad. Under the revision, `` the use of capital punishment will be curtailed,'' <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> said in an international news broadcast. `` Death sentences will be issued to those who committed premeditated murder in aggravating circumstances.'' The Soviet radio also said that `` with a view to liberalizing legislation, it was decided to replace imprisonment, wherever possible, with other disciplinary measures and fines.'' Radio <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> said the draft of the revised criminal code will be completed soon, and that the result will be submitted for public discussion. It said there are also plans to widen the role of defense lawyers during pre-trial investigations and to increase the size of juries. The typical Soviet criminal trial is presided over by a judge and two `` people's assessors.'' Although equal in theory to the judge, the assessors commonly defer to his greater knowledge of jurisprudence. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, 57, named <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief in 1985, is a 1955 graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s law school, the nation's most prestigious.
</TEXT>
