<HEAD>Attorney Says Driver Will Carry Burden Rest of Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The pickup truck driver indicted in a fiery bus crash that killed 27 people is relieved that the charges do not carry a possible death sentence, his lawyer said. `` He could n't sleep the night before wondering if he would live or be put to death,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Summers </PERSON>, attorney for <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>. `` He's had that answered.'' <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>, 35, pleaded innocent on 27 murder counts and 58 other charges filed by a <LOCATION> Carroll </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> grand jury Friday. Prosecutors had said after the May 14 crash they would seek capital murder charges that could have led to a death penalty. But state Attorney General <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowan </PERSON> said, `` After investigating into the law and evidence, we concluded it would not be appropriate to make this a death-penalty case.'' <PERSON> Cowan </PERSON> indicated authorities did not feel the crime was premeditated. <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>'s bond was set at $ 270,000 cash. The non-murder counts include 44 counts of wanton endangerment, 13 counts of assault and one count of driving under the influence of alcohol. If <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> had been indicted and convicted of capital murder, he could have been sent to the electric chair. The lesser murder charge carries a possible prison sentence of 20 years to life. Referring to the lesser charge, <PERSON> Summers </PERSON> said: `` This has taken a burden off him. The burden of what happened that night will never be off him.'' <PERSON> Cowan </PERSON> said if <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> were sentenced to life on one murder count, he would have to serve at least 12 years before being eligible for parole. Also Friday, the state medical examiner announced in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION> that the 24 children and three adults killed in the crash died of smoke inhalation after the bus and the truck, which was going the wrong way, collided on Interstate 71 near <LOCATION> Carrollton </LOCATION>. The bus, owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Radcliff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> of God church, was returning from an outing to an amusement park in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. The examiner, Dr. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>, said that alcohol was found in the bodies of four children, but he attributed this to a natural process and not drinking. `` I believe the alcohol showed up because of the post-mortem fermentation of blood sugar,'' <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said, adding that the children probably had not drunk alcoholic beverages. The recommendation for capital murder had been made by <ORGANIZATION> Carroll </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commonwealth </ORGANIZATION> Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ackman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who suffered a heart attack shortly after the accident, prompting the attorney general's office to take over the case <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Richwalsky </PERSON>, the case's chief prosecutor, said he met with more than 40 relatives of the victims Thursday night to explain the less serious charge. Asked if any of the families were disappointed with the decision, <PERSON> Richwalsky </PERSON> said, `` I ca n't say that. We had a frank and candid discussion. If anyone was disappointed or disagreed, they did n't verbalize it to me.''
</TEXT>
