<FIRST>r a AM-MustardPickpockets     07-23 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mustard Pickpockets,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Nab Two Alleged Pickpockets Using Mustard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two groups of pickpockets armed with mustard have been arrested at <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, where they had been preying on foreign tourists, a <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. The arrests were made Friday night by an undercover team fighting a rash of incidents over the past six weeks involving mainly Japanese tourists, said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchese </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. A technique becoming common among pickpockets is to discreetly squirt the intended victim with mustard or ketchup, then point it out and pretend to help him clean up. While the person is distracted, his pocket is picked or his bags stolen. The first group was arrested about 7:45 p.m. when undercover <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Authority </LOCATION> police saw three men and a woman crowd a Japanese woman in the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worldport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Terminal </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Marchese </PERSON> said. The woman had just gotten off a plane from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and had her luggage with her. Two of the men engaged her in conversation while a third was feeling her luggage, according to the report filed by <ORGANIZATION> PA </ORGANIZATION> Detective <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodstein </PERSON>. Police moved in to arrest the four, all from <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, when the woman pickpocket took out a jar of mustard and opened it, <PERSON> Marchese </PERSON> said. Five minutes later, police saw three men approach a man who had just disembarked from the same plane. `` One man squirted mustard on his sleeve, the second began wiping it off,'' <PERSON> Marchese </PERSON> said. Police moved in as the third man went for the victim's bag. Thre three ran out of the terminal but their car was stopped as it was trying to leave the airport. The seven were all charged with jostling, a Class A misdemeanor punishable by up to one year in jail upon conviction, he said. The undercover operation at <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> will continue, <PERSON> Marchese </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
