<SECOND>AM-Moslem Pilgrimage,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annual Moslem Pilgrimage Comes to Climax</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MECCA, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of thousands of white-robed Moslems prayed, chanted and listened to sermons on Mount <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> in 108-degree heat Saturday during the climax of the annual pilgrimage to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said there were protests in the holy city, but a <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> official denied the report. For the second time since Wednesday, <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio said there were political demonstrations against the ruling Saudi family and against the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The Iranian government-run radio also claimed police `` attacked'' some demonstrators. Saudi authorities, however, said the pilgrimage, or hajj, proceeded in `` peace and security.'' The pilgrims on Saturday ascended to <LOCATION> Nimra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mosque </LOCATION> on Mount <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> after trekking from <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, nine miles away. Smiling men and women draped in their seamless white pieces of cloth brandished copies of the Koran, Moslems' holy book, during the ceremony inside the mosque. The ceremony was broadcast live on <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> television and via satellite. In their midst were Saudi security men, dressed in green fatigues and caps. Authorities said 20,000 of them guarded the pilgrimage. The pilgrimage season officially began July 15 with the sighting of the crescent moon, marking the start of the Moslem holy month of Eid al-Adha. The `` Wukuf,'' or standing at <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, represents the culmination of the annual hajj, which all of the world's 850 million Moslems are expected to make at least once if they can afford it. The culmination includes the stoning of the devil, in commemoration of the prophet <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON>'s refusal to be tempted into disobeying <PERSON> God </PERSON>'s order that he sacrifice his son. On Sunday, after slaughtering sheep to represent the sacrifice of a sheep instead of <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON>'s son, the pilgrims begin a four-day feast. Prayer leader <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel-Aziz </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Sheikh </PERSON> called upon Moslems to respect and maintain the sanctity of <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>'s Grand Mosque as `` Allah has made it a place of refuge and security.'' Outside Nimra Mosque, waves of black and colored umbrellas shaded pilgrims from the sun as loudspeakers broadcast the ceremony. The temperature was about five degrees cooler than average for this time of year, but many cases of heat exhaustion and sunstroke were reported. On Friday, the pilgrims gathered for prayers at the Grand Mosque in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, which harbors the <LOCATION> Kaaba </LOCATION>, Islam's holiest shrine. It was after those prayers, according to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio, that hundreds of pilgrims demonstrated in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> against the deaths last year of 402 people, mostly Iranian pilgrims, in the holy city. Saudi authorities said many of those killed last year were trampled in a stampede, and they denied Iranian claims that police opened fire on the march. Parts of the latest report by the <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio, monitored by the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, were indistinct, but monitors said they heard no reference to injuries. `` Hundreds of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Turk </LOCATION>, Afghan, Pakistani and American pilgrims demonstrated in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> today -LRB- Friday -RRB-, chanting slogans.. and carrying placards condemning the <PERSON> Al-Saud </PERSON> regime in their killing of over 400 pilgrims of the holy sanctuary last year in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>,'' <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio said. It added: `` According to received reports, the Saudi regime's police ... subjected the demonstrators to severe control and surrounded them In some sections they attacked the ranks of the marchers.'' Government-run Saudi radio quoted an unidentified official source as saying the report was `` made up'' and one of a series of `` lies and fabrications'' broadcast by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to create tension. Gen. <PERSON> Abdullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Sheikh </PERSON>, director general of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> security, said there were no incidents. Prince <PERSON> Majed </PERSON>, governor of <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, issued a statement to the radio hailing the `` success'' of the hajj rituals. By Saudi count, there are 762,755 pilgrims from more than 130 Moslem nations who converged on the kingdom this year, joining an estimated half million from within <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. There were about 1,000 American pilgrims, according to estimates by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consulate </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jiddah </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> port city about 40 miles from <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>. Non-Moslems are barred from <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
