<HEAD>What Began With A Question Mark Ended With An Exclamation Point</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, His nomination, to include Bentsen.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrats, who began their quadrennial convention with the threat of discord, headed home in dramatic unity to fight the fall battle for the White House. `` This has been a great convention and it sets the stage for a great Democratic win in November,'' the star attraction, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, told weary delegates gathered for one last party early Friday. His nomination and that of the man he picked as his running mate, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, were guaranteed coming into <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, but the atmosphere in which the ticket would be formed was uncertain. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s bus caravan rolled in Saturday with the runner-up in the primaries unsure whether he `` had a place at the table.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> arrived Sunday but refused to meet with the edgy <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> until he sat down with his trusted advisers to assess preliminary talks between the two camps. Republicans had a `` truth squad'' in town and took advantage of the apparent rift to boast of divided Democrats and a nominee-to-be powerless to control his convention. But a show of unity just hours before <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> gaveled the party's 40th convention to order on Monday night ended most talk of discord, although Republicans continued to assert <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was stealing the show. After a nearly three-hour meeting Monday, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> declared their differences resolved, with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> promising <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> a role in the fall campaign and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in turn promising his support. `` We did not come here for fireworks; we came here for noble works,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. With that, the convention opened _ to verbal fireworks, all aimed at the Republicans. Keynote speaker <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> pumped up the more than 4,000 delegates with fiery rhetoric that lampooned <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s claim of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> as his home state and portrayed the vice president as a do-nothing member of a disgraced administration. `` I want to announce to the nation that in a little more than 100 days the Reagan-Meese-Deaver-Nofziger-Poindexter-North-Weinberger-Watt-Gorsuch-Lavelle-Stockman-Haig-Bork-Noriega-George <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> era will be over,'' the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> treasurer said to thunderous applause. The redeemed <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> made a prime-time appearance, too, adding his call for moral government to a convention with a deliberate Southern flavor. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had his night Tuesday, declaring himself qualified for the presidency and predicting he would occupy the White House in the future while urging his backers to support <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in the fall. In a show of respect, many <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> delegates gave up their hall passes to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> alternates and supporters and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> placards were kept low while a sea of red proclaimed `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>!'' Despite that gesture, not all of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s backers got into the Omni convention hall. Thousands were kept out after <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s fire marshal decided too many people had already been let in, a problem that continued throughout the four-day gathering. Monday's detente had removed the potential for acrimony Wednesday, when <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won the party's blessing to take on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. All that was left was to crown the nominee, and after the rousing speeches of <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, there was some worry the star of the show might be upstaged. But actress cousin <PERSON> Olympia </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, in a supporting role once again, warmed the audience with an introduction of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> the frugal family man, and when the standard-bearer entered the hall he was filled with emotion that carried over into the speech of his lifetime. His eyes welled and his voice cracked when he talked of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream of his late father _ a <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> immigrant who arrived at <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> with $ 25 and rose to become a wealthy doctor. His smile was broad as he waved to his 84-year-old mother, herself an immigrant, and his wife and children gathered in a skybox above the made-for-TV rostrum at a made-for-TV convention. `` I'm a product of that dream,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said on his dream night. `` My friends, we're going to forge a new era of greatness for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spoke forcefully about his themes of jobs and day care and health care and competence, and sternly about his commitment to public service and his perceived lack of such in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. No stranger to television or teleprompters, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' delivery was as carefully choreographed as the swirling lights and patriotic music that had entertained the delegates before him. He ended with an Athenian pledge to strength, honesty and integrity, but not before allowing screaming delegates to interrupt repeatedly with a chant Democrats will surely take into the fall campaign: `` Where was <PERSON> George </PERSON>? Where was <PERSON> George </PERSON>?'' _ a reference to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s professed ignorance of administration blunders. In the end, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was joined by his family, then <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and his family, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and his family, the <ORGANIZATION> Carters </ORGANIZATION> and other contenders in what began as a crowded race for the nomination and ended with the crowning of the man who likens the race to a marathon. The confetti fell, the balloons followed and the Democrats went home happy.
