<HEAD>Dukakis Adviser Said `Go Slowly' During Convention Speech</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-CVN-Convention Overview Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Just before <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> stepped onto the convention podium for the most important moment of his political life, longtime friend <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> gave him two words of final advice: `` Go slowly.'' He meant it. Despite a highly successful political career and three terms as governor, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> carried to the stage at the conclusion of the Democratic National Convention a reputation for stepping on good lines and doing better at reducing political emotions than inspiring them. <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> wanted his friend to avoid what he saw as a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> rhetorical pitfall of hurrying his speech, of talking so fast the words carried no punch. His friend listened. `` He did it,'' <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> said, still beaming with the enthusiasm of the convention's final night as he headed out of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and into the new Democratic campaign. `` He paced himself.'' In so doing, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> answered the doubters who questioned his ability to move an audience and to reveal enough soul to lead a political cause. While the display of soaring rhetoric and moving delivery may prove short-lived, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> achieved it on the night he most needed it _ claiming the Democratic presidential nomination. Indeed, at his first campaign stop the next day in <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> seemed to revert to his sometimes bland and wooden delivery. But <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides believe that in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> last week they achieved all they could have: a united convention, a supportive <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, and a moving prime-time television hour in which the candidate revealed himself to the nation. <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON>, the senior adviser and campaign chairman who has been <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' friend since their days at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, said the candidate seemed a little surprised by the emotion evoked in the convention hall and by his own success. `` He said, ` I walked out there ... and it exploded.' `` You know, how many people get nominated for the presidency? I do n't think he quite knew what to expect,'' <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> said. In fact, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' speech was a departure in style from the moment he stepped into view. He walked slowly from side to side on the stage, accepting the cheers by slowing raising one arm and then the other. That modest wave was more expressive than <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had been all week. `` He threw his hands up _ you know <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> does n't usually do that,'' <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> said. `` When he did that, the whole place exploded.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> used many of the lines he has used since the campaign began in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, referring to his immigrant parents and invoking the imagery of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s election nearly three decades ago. But with the aid of speechwriters <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodward </PERSON>, he dressed up those references in newer phrasing and, in delivering them, seemed to connect with his audience in a way that communicated more emotion than before. `` Most of it was <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' language ... with better cadence, better rhythm,'' <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> said. His closing remarks _ a reference to keynoter <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>' granddaughter, to <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s five children and to his own expected grandchild _ were penned in by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> himself after Tuesday night's speech by <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, according to <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON>. A day later, he traveled to the convention hall and spent three and a half hours checking out the podium and rehearsing before a TelePrompTer in a private room that was a replica of the stage. He stayed, practicing, for two hours more than he had scheduled. When his speech was over Thursday night, aides and observers pronounced it as good as he had ever been. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had an explanation for his adviser <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON>. `` He said the crowd does it to you once in a while,'' <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> said. `` He was sort of choked.''
