<TEXT>
 In 1984, at age 13, <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Lau </PERSON> was one of 12 winners in an essay contest who got to meet Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. At 16, she had become a runaway supporting herself and her drug habit with prostitution. `` I told myself this was n't prostitution, it's just give and take,'' <PERSON> Lau </PERSON> said. `` It was there, and I had about 25 cents in my pocket, and I had an amazing capacity at first to just block it out.'' Then she realized that her writing was taking a back seat to drugs. `` That totally destroyed me,'' said <PERSON> Lau </PERSON>. After an unsuccessful suicide attempt, she wound up in a hospital a year ago. She decided to stop doing drugs and resume writing. Now, at 17, she has a <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> grant for $ 13,000 -LRB- more than $ 10,700 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- for her writing and a contract with a <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> publisher for her first book, to be called `` Small Lives: The Diary of a Street Kid.'' She also has more dubious signs of success _ legal problems and lawyer's fees, over which she has little control because she is now a ward of the state. She left home because of friction with her parents, possibly the reason social caseworkers decided not to return her to her parents. And since she was a juvenile not with her family, Canadian law required that she be made a ward of the state. She said officials in the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> have told her they are not sure she can handle the grant, which comes out to about $ 1,100 -LRB- more than $ 900 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- a month. She is negotiating with public trustee <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Rumsey </PERSON> and the ministry superintendent over how her grant should be paid. `` It's hard enough being a writer and not getting a paycheck every two weeks, and the rewards are few and far between,'' <PERSON> Lau </PERSON> said after she learned of the award last week. `` Then when you get rewarded, they take it away from you. `` I felt like I was more of a human out there -LRB- on the street -RRB- than I am now. At least I had some control.'' `` I'm supposed to be jumping up and down, but I feel like every time I do something that everybody should be happy about they have an anxiety attack,'' she said. `` They're afraid I'm going to take the money and blow it, which is n't even feasible.'' `` If I went out and got a job that paid $ 1,100 a month, they would n't come after me and say, ` You're making too much money,' so how is this different? Is n't this work?'' she said. `` We want to make sure the monies are used for the purposes intended by the grant,'' <PERSON> Rumsey </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` We would be responsible in looking after the funds as trustees.'' <PERSON> Lau </PERSON> also receives $ 480 a month in social assistance. She pays $ 300 for rent and uses the rest for writing expenses. `` When I get my check I buy my supplies first _ paper, ribbons, stamps. I'm constantly submitting my short stories and poems to magazines, and I'm not going to give that up, but it's amazing how much it costs,'' <PERSON> Lau </PERSON> said. Her first encounter with the problems of being a ward of the state came when the public trustee hired lawyer <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> McColl </PERSON> to review her contract with literary agent <PERSON> Denise </PERSON> <PERSON> Bukowski </PERSON>, her book contract with <ORGANIZATION> Collins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> and her manuscript for any potential libel. <PERSON> McColl </PERSON>'s $ 175-an-hour fee is to be paid from <PERSON> Lau </PERSON>'s advance on royalties from <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, although the size of the advance was not known. <PERSON> Bukowski </PERSON> said the lawyer is unnecessary because the publisher has its own lawyers to check the manuscript, butMcColl said he redrafted the agent's contract, approved the publisher's contract. `` We have a responsibility to protect the child,'' <PERSON> Rumsey </PERSON> said. `` The publisher may well have counsel, but that does n't necessarily mean the best advice is going to go to the infant.''
