<HEAD>Hungarian Leader, Seeking Closer Ties to West, Visits Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hungarian leader <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, eager to strengthen ties to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> as part of an ambitious reform program, comes to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this week on the first visit by a Hungarian of his rank since the country came under <ORGANIZATION> communist </ORGANIZATION> rule 40 years ago. Since becoming premier in June 1987, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> has moved decisively to pursue economic and political openings to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, where the image of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> for years had been largely shaped by the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s smashing of an anti-Moscow uprising in 1956. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>'s 11-day, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> visit, which began last week and took him to <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, has its high point Wednesday when has a luncheon with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> during a White House visit. He also will meet with Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, congressional leaders and Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, who became <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> general secretary last May in addition to premier, is the first <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact leader to make an official visit to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> since 1978 when President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> received Romanian leader <PERSON> Nicolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceaucescu </PERSON>. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, 57, is from the same generation as <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and, like the Soviet leader, he has called for a new era of openness and economic restructuring. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, insisting on anonymity, said that <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> will be encouraged during his talks here to continue his announced policy of seeking increased trade with and investment from Western countries. To improve efficiency, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> has been pushing market-oriented approaches but this and other measures have increased unemployment levels in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. Another problem area for <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> is <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s $ 11 billion foreign debt. Among economic goals approved by the party since <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>' accession are more foreign investment, fewer restrictions on the ownership of foreign capital, an expansion of private initiatives, and a greater voice for consumers In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> last Wednesday, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> witnessed the signing of a $ 115 million joint venture between a Hungarian entity and <ORGANIZATION> Guardian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, an Illinois-based glass manufacturer. `` We have seen science and technology tear down borders between countries and even continents ... and those who come to recognize this will be in an advantageous position,'' said <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> also met with officials of <ORGANIZATION> MacDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to discuss a larger presence in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> for the fast food giant. The firm already has a thriving operation in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> has been courting West European leaders as well. He was received warmly on visits to <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and three weeks ago, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> became the first communist country to reach an agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. The accord will gradually allow expanded Hungarian exports to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> by removing present tariffs and quotas between now and 1995. Still, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> is intent on maintaining its traditional role as a member of the Soviet-led <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION>. More than three decades after the Soviet invasion of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, an estimated 65,000 Soviet troops are deployed there. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence officials recently received indications that the Soviets were planning to withdraw these forces but thus far there has been no announcement.
