 A gas station owner who was enraged by the town council's refusal to give him a car-wash permit shot and killed the mayor of this northern Italian village and then committed suicide, police said Saturday. Authorities said <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> <PERSON> Cotter </PERSON>, 58, shouted at Mayor <PERSON> Luigi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodigari </PERSON> during a town council meeting Friday night and left the building only after officials threatened to call police. Colzate is a town of about 1,600 people, 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>. After the meeting, <PERSON> Cotter </PERSON>, 58, approached the car in which the 46-year-old mayor was sitting in the parking lot, threw open the door and fired 13 times with a pistol, police said. <PERSON> Cotter </PERSON> also shot the driver, <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonfanti </PERSON>, who heads the local chapter of the Christian Democrat party, police said. He was in serious condition.
