<HEAD>Honeymoon is Over, But Home Loan Bank Board Chairman Still
Optimistic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>, the nearly bald regulator of the nation's savings institutions, is known as an optimist by the comb he still carries. A year ago, Wall pushed hard for and was appointed to the chairmanship of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, a job only a cockeyed optimist would want at a time of unprecedented industry losses and mounting S & amp; L failures. To prove his credentials, he had only to pull out his pocket comb and make a rueful reference to the few, wispy strands of hair on the top of his head. Despite a year filled with criticism and difficulties, <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said in a recent interview, `` We have n't had any surprises'' and, asked about his comb, he said smiling, `` I still have it.'' The 48-year-old former Republican staff director of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> enjoyed something of a honeymoon after he took office last July, replacing <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, an aloof administrator disliked by his staff, the industry and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. A big part of <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>'s problem was outside his control. His agency was out of money and could n't do much to stop the savings industry from sliding into a morass. Wall came in with a number of pluses: a squeaky clean image, a reputation for candor and enthusiasm and, most importantly, money to work with. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last August provided for a $ 10.8 billion, industry-financed infusion over three years into the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which guarantees deposits up to $ 100,000 in 3,100 institutions. Now, the honeymoon is drawing to a close and there is no shortage of critics. But even the critics acknowledge the bank board's Herculean task. Insolvent institutions account for more than 10 percent of the industry and losses in 1988 are expected to top the $ 7.6 billion, post-Depression record of last year. `` I think he has the toughest job in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government and everything has to be seen in that context,'' said <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemel </PERSON>, a former bank board, economist now an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Earlier this month, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> put Wall through a grueling session when he revealed he had more than doubled his estimate of the cost of closing or merging insolvent S & amp; Ls in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the state where the industry is sickest. In May, <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> was being criticized for being too optimistic by insisting it was too soon to tell if his agency needed more money, while private analysts were calling for a taxpayer bailout. Democrats were suggesting there were political motivations for pushing debate over the problem into the next administration. Wall's refiguring less than two months later boosted the pricetag for cleaning up the entire industry nationwide from $ 22.7 billion to $ 30.9 billion, more in line with the $ 26 billion to $ 36 billion estimate of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> and within range of the $ 40 billion to $ 75 billion estimated by private analysts. But he was still criticized for the change. `` Now you see it, now you do n't,'' complained a frustrated Rep. <PERSON> Fernand </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> St </PERSON> <PERSON> Germain </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Wall, in the interview, said the new estimate was based on new information, adding, `` We're trying to present a realistic view of the problem. We're trying to keep everyone's fever in proper perspective.'' Despite the higher projected pricetag, Wall is still saying the <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> could have enough money to handle the problem. But to do that, he has had to offend another important constituency _ executives of the industry he regulates. Savings institutions were already disturbed by <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>'s support of legislation extending by one year the moratorium preventing them from converting from <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> membership to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The healthier <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> insures deposits in commercial banks, charging member institutions less than half of the assessment charged by <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION>. Industry executives objected when they found out Wall intended to cover the cost of his his newly increased estimate of costs by extending the special assessment thrift institutions are paying to recapitalize <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> to 1998. Originally, it was scheduled to be phased out by 1991. B.R. <PERSON> Beeksma </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> InterWest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, and vice chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, said the extension would be misguided. `` What's necessary for this industry to survive in the long run is the ability to attract new capital. ... Recently, the entire profits of our business have been made available to solve the problems of <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION>. Yet we simply have to have profits because we ca n't attract capital unless we have them,'' he said. Wall has also been criticized for moving too slowly in closing or finding buyers for insolvent institutions in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, which alone accounted for $ 3.5 billion of the industry's $ 3.8 billion loss in the first three months of this year. `` It's just taking too long to get the deals done,'' said <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ely </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, consultant. `` And by being so slow, they are reducing the number of people who are even willing to look at a deal.'' `` We're critical of ourselves in that regard,'' <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said, but he pointed to three large transactions in the state in May and June and promised the pace would pick up. Since money began flowing into <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> coffers in October, <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said his agency has closed, merged or otherwise resolved the problems of 65 S & amp; Ls. And, conservatively, he said the board would resolve the cases of another 100 institutions by the end of this year, about one third of the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls considered insolvent under regulatory rules. `` If you had asked me about three months ago, I would have said we're getting a lot of great promises, but not much action,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Butera </PERSON>, chief lobbyist of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>, a trade group. `` But in the last three months, he has really come through.''
