<FIRST>r a AM-GuardianshipConference     07-23 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guardianship Conference,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bar Conference Recommends Sweeping Change In Gardianship Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RACINE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A national conference sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> called Saturday for major changes in the nation's guardianship system, including expanded legal rights and representation for the old and disabled. Forty-four experts, including attorneys, psychiatrists, judges, researchers and government officials, also cautioned that judges and lawyers were often `` quantitatively and qualitatively inadequate'' in performing their guardianship duties and recommended greater awareness of flaws in the system. <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> officials attending the National Guardianship Symposium: A Response to The Associated Press Inquiry said the meeting was a result of growing concerns about the nation's guardianship system, including the findings of the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s 50-state investigation of abuses in court-ordered guardianships. `` It's the perception of many professionals that the guardianship system is not meeting the needs of some people and may be abusing the rights of others, as demonstrated by the information in the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> report,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Nevelowf </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubler </PERSON>, a commissioner with that <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s Commission on the Legal Problems of the Elderly. Last year's AP series found many of the 300,000 to 400,000 elderly under guardianship in this country are stripped of their rights and placed under the power of a guardian without the same court protections given those facing criminal charges. An AP review of 2,200 case files also found the courts often failed to do their job monitoring guardianships, leaving elderly wards prey to financial and physical abuse at the hands of their guardians. The three-day conference issued 36 recommendations for change in the system. Among them: _ Legal representation for all those facing guardianship. The group said attorneys should represent the wishes of clients. The AP investigation found lawyers often dismiss the rights of their clients facing guardianship. _ The elimination of age, economic status, medical diagnosis or `` eccentricity'' as sole reasons for placing someone under guardianship. While many state laws permit guardianships for reasons of age alone, the conference stressed that guardianship be used only when the person can no longer care of themselves. _ Greater efforts by judges, lawyers and court personnel to understand the problems of the elderly. The courts were urged to tailor proceedings for those with poor eyesight or hard of hearing. _ Attempts to find alternatives to guardianship in cases where it does not serve the interests of the proposed ward. The AP study found people are often placed under guardianship to assure payments to nursing homes or limit liability to hospitals. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wexler </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> law professor and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on the Mentally Disabled said the recommendations come at a time when the guardianship system is coming under greater scrutiny. `` As the population ages and a larger number of people has experience with this system it has to grow in importance,'' he said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, commission director, said the recommendations would go on to various <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> groups for review with hopes that state legislatures and individual courts would amend laws and practices. `` It's one of the first volleys being fired in this issue,'' he said. Since the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s series last fall, some 20 states have either passed or considered legislation to reform guardianship systems in their courts. Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., has drafted legislation setting federal guardianship standards for the courts Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonker </PERSON>, D-Wash., also has drafted recommended standards for the system The conference was sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on the Mentally Disabled and <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Legal Problems of the Elderly and was hosted by the <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
