 Imprisoned black leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> saw relatives and fellow activists on Saturday after earlier rejecting government-sanctioned visits to protest a ban on celebrations of his 70th birthday. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s wife <PERSON> Winnie </PERSON>, their daughter, two grandchildren and an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> attorney who represents the <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> family's interests visited <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Pollsmoor </LOCATION> Prison for 80 minutes. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> also met with <PERSON> Yusuf </PERSON> and <PERSON> Amina </PERSON> <PERSON> Cachalia </PERSON>, activists who in the 1950s waged with him a campaign against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s policy of apartheid, or racial segregation. The Cachalias last saw <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> in 1962, the year he was imprisoned. They had been applying for 15 years for permission to meet him again. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> is serving a life sentence for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white-led government as a leader of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the country's main guerrilla group. Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> said prison officials had the best intentions in offering her husband a special meeting with nine of his relatives on his birthday Monday. But she said <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> rejected the offer to protest the government's ban on celebrations of his birthday and to protest the detention of pro-Mandela activists. Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, of High Point, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> agreed to grant power of attorney to him to protect the use of the <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> family name and its interests worldwide. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, who announced a similar agreement with Mrs. <PERSON> Man