<FIRST>u i AM-NeWin-Profile 1stLd-Writethru a0528 07-23 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ne Win-Profile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0528,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma Leader Wielded Power For More Than a Quarter-Century</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to ADD that rioting cited as reason for
resignation and CLARIFY that advancing age, sted poor health
another reason. Pickup 4th graf pvs ``Born Shu...''; SUBS last graf
``He cited...'' to CONFORM</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ne Win, a one-time military hero and <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s undisputed ruler for 26 years, relinquished his grip on power in a country shaken by mounting political unrest and economic decline. Citing anti-government rioting and advancing age, Ne Win announced Saturday he was resigning as chairman of the country's sole political party, the <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Ne Win, whose name means `` Brilliant as the Sun'' in <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION>, called for a referendum on ending one-party rule that could shake the very political foundations he established after seizing power in a 1962 military coup. Born <PERSON> Shu </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> on May 14, 1911 in the central Burmese town of <LOCATION> Paungbe </LOCATION>, he took the name Ne Win after entering revolutionary politics in what was then a British colony. Ne Win worked briefly as a postal clerk after failing in medical studies. He joined the anti-British movement and became one of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s `` Thirty Comrades,'' who traveled secretly to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for military training in the early days of World War II. Returning to <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON> and his comrades fought first alongside the Japanese against the British, but then turned against their teachers after realizing that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> would also colonize rather than liberate the Burmese. Ne Win rose quickly in the military and became chief of staff of the Burmese armed forces in 1949, the year after <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> gained independence. He came to the political forefront in 1958 when the military pushed aside an ineffective prime minister and established a caretaker government in a country wracked by poverty and ethnic division. As promised, elections were held in 1960. Nu, soon to become Ne Win's archrival, won the post of prime minister. Ne Win, who had the makings of a popular leader, staged a coup in 1962, jailed Nu and vowed to lead his country on a neutralist, egalitarian and moralistic `` <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION> to Socialism.'' Once known as a playboy and gambler, Ne Win banned gambling, closed nightclubs and preached strict, traditional morality. This did not stop him from enjoying horse racing or from marrying six times. He moved quickly toward socialism. Private businesses were nationalized, generally with little or no compensation, and the central government attempted to run everything from the vital rice trade to light manufacturing. Foreign private investment ceased, and foreigners were carefully screened before being allowed into the country. Some charged that <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> leaders, including Ne Win, could not shake a post-colonial syndrome that included xenophobia. Ne Win became president under a constitution written in 1974. Although he retired from the military in 1972, Ne Win maintained effective control of the capable, well-organized armed forces that served as his chief instrument of control. When anti-government riots erupted from time to time, Ne Win moved ruthlessly to suppress them. Thousands of dissenters were jailed. Although most were later releaed, there have been persistent allegations of human rights violations. Fearing assassination, Ne Win rarely appeared in public, traveled under tight security and never gave a press conference. He became a recluse and spent much of his time in a heavily-guarded lakeside villa on the edge of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. About the only time <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> residents could catch a glimpse of their leader was inside his heavily guarded limousine on the way to play golf. He also kept potential rivals at bay, by firing or jailing up-and-coming leaders and demanding loyalty from subordinates. Burmese say <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON> is both a shrewd, calculating political tactician and a personality given to sudden outbursts of anger. His moves were rarely foreshadowed. His resignation from the presidency in 1981 was unexpected, as was Saturday's announcement that he would step down from his one remaining post, the chairmanship of the party. He cited poor health on the first occasion and advancing age on Saturday. There have been unconfirmed reports of heart, kidney and stomach problems. But after 1981, Ne Win gave no indication that declining health had lessened his grip on power.
</TEXT>
