<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The rupture and explosion of two underground gas pipelines forced the temporary evacuation of 200 people and and left a crater 30 feet in diameter and 25 feet deep in a highway, authorities said Saturday. No injuries resulted from the Friday evening blast, which sent flames up to 300 feet in the air, said <LOCATION> Shawnee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sheriff </LOCATION>'s Deputy <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Denton </PERSON> The residents of an apartment complex and trailer court were allowed to return to their undamaged homes after the fire was extinguished about 1 a.m. Saturday, <PERSON> Denton </PERSON> said. The explosion blasted a crater into the northbound lanes of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 75 near <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION>, he said. One pipeline carried methane and the other propane. Officials of <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, Okla.-based <ORGANIZATION> Mid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the pipelines' owner, met with city officials and emergency personnel Saturday to determine the cause of the rupture and the extent of damage, <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> said. Firefighters initially could not approach the ruptured lines because of the heat. They extinguished nearby field fires ignited by the explosion.
