<HEAD>Jackson Leaves Atlanta, Says Convention Was `Tremendous Moment'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> headed home to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Saturday, leaving town in a decidedly more low-key manner than he entered and maintaining that his failed presidential campaign made history at the Democratic National Convention. The civil rights leader refused to speculate on whether he would seek public office again, saying that his priority now is to work for the Democratic ticket in the fall presidential race. `` My focus now is on the fall campaign,'' he told reporters as he left a downtown <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> hotel. `` We'll be spending a lot of time organizing for voter registration, issue interpretation, involving people _ many for the first time _ and a big turnout for the fall campaign.'' Of his post-election plans, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, `` We'll have to determine what will happen, based on the outcome of the campaign. But we take this journey one phase at a time.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> took members of his family, campaign staffers and journalists who covered his bid for the Democratic presidential nomination to <PERSON> Paschal </PERSON>'s, a well-known, black-owned hotel and restaurant for lunch. The entourage then headed for <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, west of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, where a chartered jet took off shortly after 2 p.m. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, dressed in cuffed blue jeans, sandals and a red, white and blue shirt, appeared at ease, accepting well-wishers and posing for photographers. A few reporters and photographers covered his departure and about 10 people gathered at the airport to bid <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> farewell. The casual scene contrasted sharply with the thunderous entrance to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> made by <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> one week earlier. A motorcade of buses brought the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> campaign to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> July 16, two days before the start of the Democratic convention. He addressed thousands of cheering supporters in <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, asserting that <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, then assured of the nomination, must give <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> a stronger voice in the party. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and vice presidential nominee Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> met on Monday and peace was made. Though <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s name was placed in nomination at the convention, he later pledged support for the Dukakis-Bentsen ticket <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said Saturday his campaign made great gains in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. He said blacks and others previously outside the party mainstream will have unprecedented involvement in the fall campaign. And he noted that several <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> platform positions were adopted. `` We can leave <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> with a real sense of inspiration because of the expansion of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, more inclusion, involvement in the campaign at all levels, vertically and horizontally. And also helping to determine the course, the priorities _ being in the room where poilicy is debated and priorities are set. `` This is a trmemendous moment for us,'' he said.
