<DATELINE>STUART, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retired naval architect <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Petzold </PERSON> and a ship he helped design 44 years ago will soon be neighbors. A <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> demolition team will send the U.S.S. <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON> to the sea floor off the coast of <LOCATION> Martin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> on Sunday to serve as an artificial reef. The site is just a few miles from <PERSON> Petzold </PERSON>'s home. `` It's crazy. It really is crazy. I ca n't believe how that thing is following me,'' <PERSON> Petzold </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Petzold </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Stuart </LOCATION> resident for 10 years, designed the ship with colleagues at <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Architects </ORGANIZATION> in 1944 and followed its career through World War II, when he was a civilian in charge of monitoring ship performance during battle. After the war, his decision to keep the ship in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> fleet enabled the vessel to build up a military record that includes service in the Korean conflict and during the Cuban missile crisis. `` Here in the twilight of my life, that baby doll is going to be right out there,'' he said. To add to the coincidence, his father-in-law, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, was the <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON>'s first full-time captain.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 6-year-old boy has his own theory on the extinction of dinosaurs. `` My theory is that God killed off all the dinosaurs so there would be room for all the other animals,'' says <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Shuster </PERSON>. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, shared his theory with millions of television viewers during an appearance Friday on the `` Tonight Show with <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>.'' `` That's not a bad theory,'' <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> said. `` It's as good as any other.'' <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> was invited to appear on the show after its producers heard of his 35-minute lecture on dinosaurs to second-grade students in Fremont. <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, asked <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> if he knew <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> hailed from the Cornhusker State `` about 150 miles'' from <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>. `` Everybody who knows I'm going here tells me that,'' <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> said, seemingly unimpressed. The young dinosaur expert said he normally is not allowed to stay up late enough to watch the show, but was given special permission when he found out he would be a guest. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> said he likes the Tyrannosaurus <PERSON> Rex </PERSON> best of all dinosaurs `` because he was the king of the reptiles. He ate meat. He was 29-feet long.''
