 A soft-drink distributor who maintains he should get some of the profits from commercial products derived from his blood and body tissues says he is pleased by a court ruling that may lead to that. `` To me, this -LRB- ruling -RRB- is the ultimate vindication of the rightness of what we're trying to do,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said Friday after learning the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> 2nd <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> reinstated his suit against the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California-Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, 43, claims Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Golde </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION> never informed him of the value of his blood while using it to develop a product that scientists say offers considerable hope for treating cancer and AIDS. His attorney in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Zackey </PERSON>, said the ruling was unprecedented. `` This is the first time an appellate court has ruled that a patient has an interest in the unique properties of his genetic material and that commercial exploitation without the patient's consent entitles the patient to sue for damages,'' <PERSON> Zackey </PERSON> said Private research companies paid <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION> $ 500,000 for exclusive access to <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s cells, <PERSON> Zackey </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Golde </PERSON> received benefits worth about $ 1.5 million, and trade sources have indicated the full line of treatments that could be developed from the cells might be worth more than $ 3 billion, the lawyer added. An attorney for <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, said he might seek reconsideration of the ruling or seek an appeal. Twelve years ago, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> learned he had a rare blood disease called hairy-cell leukemia, and in a relatively common treatment, <PERSON> Golde </PERSON> removed his spleen. From that organ, <PERSON> Golde </PERSON> discovered <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s blood possessed a previously unknown capacity for fighting disease, and for the next seven years he had the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> man frequently return to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to draw more blood. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said he never was told that researchers used his blood and tissues to patent what they called the `` Mo-cell.'' The product was developed by copying a unique characteristic found in <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s cells, a property that boosts production of certain white blood cells which, in turn, stimulate the body's first line of defense against some diseases When patients consent to the removal of organs, they also consent to disposal of the organs, including their use in research, so <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> `` had abandoned any interests in the therapeutically removed tissue,'' <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> said. Since his spleen was removed, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> has undergone no further treatment and says the disease appears to be in remission.
