<HEAD>Vets Returning to Vietnam to Clear Mine Fields</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spurred by reports that land mines are maiming and killing Vietnamese children, five veterans intend to return to <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> to help clear mine fields they laid 20 years ago. `` I do n't consider myself a Rambo type, and I do n't consider myself a <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonda </PERSON>,'' former Cpl. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Noe </PERSON> said Saturday. `` I did what I had to do, what I was told to do, during the war. `` And I'm doing what I feel is right to do now.'' <PERSON> Noe </PERSON>, a 39-year-old firefighter in <LOCATION> Stoughton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, and four fellow veterans of the 11th Marine Combat Engineering Battalion have received the Vietnamese government's approval for a two-week humanitarian mission in January. They plan to point out the perimeters of the fields they laid, provide technical expertise on mines and, if necessary, comb the jungle with metal detectors and probe the dirt with knives. <PERSON> Noe </PERSON> said they realize their actions may be dangerous and have asked the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> to reduce the risk by turning over maps of the fields. But a <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the maps either never reached the Pentagon or were tossed out long ago. `` If we kept everything back that far, this city would be buried under paper,'' said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peck </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> public affairs office in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. If that means the veterans have to rely on memories two decades old, so be it, said former <PERSON> Lance </PERSON> <PERSON> Cpl </PERSON>. <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Genna </PERSON>, 40, of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` I wo n't remember all the fields, but I'll remember the ones I worked on,'' <PERSON> Genna </PERSON> said. `` You'd be surprised how well you recall when you had ears on the back of your head and eyes on your rear end.'' Plans for the trip emerged from a September 1987 reunion in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Genna </PERSON> showed his companions a newspaper article in which the Vietnamese government estimated 3,000 people _ many of them children _ died from grenades, bombs and land mines between 1975 and 1985. Former Sgt. <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spanos </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Rosemont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, who organized the reunion, said the news hit him hard. `` I turned to one former battalion commander and said, ` Sir, did you take the mine fields out?,' and he said, ` No.' `` So I turned to the other battalion commander who relieved him and I said, ` Did you?' And he said, ` No.' So I said, ` My God, all these years have gone by, and we're still killing people over there,'' recalled <PERSON> Spanos </PERSON>. After the reunion, <PERSON> Spanos </PERSON>, 40, contacted the Vietnamese mission to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, wrote to other veterans and found an anonymous donor willing to support the mine-clearing expedition, which the veterans estimate will cost $ 30,000. Besides <PERSON> Spanos </PERSON>, <PERSON> Noe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Genna </PERSON>, the veterans who have volunteered are <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Langdon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>. All five served in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> between 1967 and 1970 The group's translator and guide will be retired Marine Lt. Col. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON>, who went to <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> last fall to help plan the mission. `` I'm supporting them because it's a humanitarian effort I agree with,'' <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON> said. `` I see this as an act of a reconciliation between two governments that have been at odds for a long time _ and who better to do it than the young men who were sent to fight the war in the first place.''
