<TEXT>
 The chairman of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Saturday denied reports that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has illegally imported heavy water for its nuclear plants, a news agency said. M.R. <PERSON> Srinivasan </PERSON> said <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has been producing heavy water since the 1960s, and it `` has been self-sufficient for her needs,'' the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. `` There is no question of importing illegally. In fact, at one stage we had exported to <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>.'' He spoke at a news conference at <LOCATION> Poona </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION>. Newspaper reports in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> have said <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> may have received the water in shipments secretly diverted from <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. Opposition party members in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> have charged that some of the Norwegian heavy water was diverted with the help of a West German firm. The shipments allegedly were diverted in the early 1980s. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has not signed the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nonproliferation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION>, and reports have suggested the heavy water could have been used to produce plutonium for making nuclear weapons. Heavy water, or deuterium oxide, looks like ordinary water but has an extra neutron. It is used to cool a nuclear reactor by moderating the speed of neutrons released in a chain reaction. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has six plan