<HEAD>Zia Accuses India of Provoking Ethnic Disturbances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON> on Saturday accused <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> of provoking ethnic violence in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s southern province of <LOCATION> Sind </LOCATION>. `` We have fundamental proof, evidence to show to our friends in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, that they have been interferring in <LOCATION> Sind </LOCATION> by trying to isolate <PERSON> Sind </PERSON> from the rest of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> said in a statement. He did not elaborate. More than 40 people have been killed in ethnic fighting in <LOCATION> Sind </LOCATION> during the past two months. In the latest incident, on July 17, the mayor of <LOCATION> Hyderabad </LOCATION> was wounded in an assassination attempt and a <LOCATION> Hyderabad </LOCATION> city councilman was killed in the attack. The shootings were followed by riots in which seven people were killed. Much of the violence has involved Moslem immigrants who fled to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> from predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Hindu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> in 1947 after the Indian subcontinent received independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and was partitioned into <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The immigrants are demanding recognition as a fifth ethnic group. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is ethnically divided into four major groups: Pathans in the northwest, Punjabis in the eastern province of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, Baluchis in the western province of <LOCATION> Baluchistan </LOCATION> and Sindhis in <LOCATION> Sind </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> noted the immigrants have been in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> more than 40 years and said: `` Why is it that now they have come all of a sudden as a group demanding its rights? Because it has been provoked as such, as a parochial element in order to advance political reasons.'' <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> denied