<HEAD>Delhi's Death Toll From Cholera Rises To 118</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Workers with spades, wheelbarrows and trucks began removing heaps of garbage from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>'s slum areas Saturday as officials reported 14 more deaths from cholera and intestinal infections. The death toll from this month's outbreak is now at least 118, and a city health spokesman said Saturday hospitals had admitted 70 more patients with cholera and other intestinal diseases. Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, who visited the affected districts Friday, has given the municipal sanitation department a deadline of three days to clean clogged drains and garbage dumps and spray pesticides over stagnant water. He accused city administrators and health officers of not doing enough to combat the epidemic. The health department spokesman, who spoke with the condition he not be identified, said 103,684 people have been inoculated in the disease-stricken zones. Trucks were collecting garbage and crews cleared the overworked drainage system. The onset of the monsoon rains in early July resulted in clogged drains in districts with inadequate sanitation facilities. Health officials blame the cholera outbreak on the contamination of wells by rainwater flowing through garbage and sewage. More than 9,140 people have sought treatment at hospitals this month for cholera and gastroenteritis, according to official figures. That is more than four times the number of such cases registered in all of July last year. Outbreaks of cholera and gastroenteritis also have occurred in northern <LOCATION> Uttar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pradesh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> states claiming 62 lives, according to news reports.
