<SECOND>AM-Brazil-US Sanctions,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazilian President Calls U.S. Trade Sanctions `Unfair'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Brazil Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> on Friday criticized as unfair a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to impose economic sanctions on <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> for refusing to recognize patents for foreign pharmaceutical products. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> started a process Friday that will lead to sanctions on $ 200 million worth of yet unspecified Brazilian goods. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the No. 1 market for Brazilian exports. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> issued a communique calling the decision `` unfair and discriminatory.'' He said it `` violates the most elementary principles of international law and the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>,'' referring to the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the Geneva-based body that promotes fair trade practices. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government was caving in to the special interests of the American pharmaceutical industry and warned the action `` tends to undermine bilateral trade relations.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> claims American drug companies lose about $ 36 million a year because <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> permits unauthorized copies of pharmaceutical products and formulas. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> denied that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies were being jeopardized. He said 85 percent of the Brazilian drug industry is foreign-owned and that American companies were the market leaders with a 35 percent share. He added that <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> may demand reparations under <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> provisions for damages caused by the sanctions. The sale of medical drugs in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> totaled $ 1.1 billion in 1987, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Brazilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. About 73 percent of that total was by foreign-owned multinationals. Of the 500 pharmaceutical companies in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, 69 are foreign-owned, the association said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision had been expected by the drug industry in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Raimundo </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Anglo-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION>. `` Only the government did n't see it coming. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> has not shown any willingness to negotiate,'' <PERSON> Raimundo </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Raimundo </PERSON>, who also is an executive of the Brazilian subsidiary of the British-owned <ORGANIZATION> Glaxo </ORGANIZATION> drug company, said the sanctions would immediately hurt Brazilian exports. `` It already is having an effect. The American importer and the Brazilian exporter do n't know what products will be on the list, so trade stalls,'' he said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> came close to slapping $ 105 million in trade sanctions on <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> earlier this year, but backed away in March when that country responded to complaints about its policies regarding importation of software products.
