<DATELINE>WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sheet of steel estimated to weigh 1,000 pounds fell on a construction worker and pinned him, but other workers got him out of the tight squeeze and he suffered only minor injuries. `` I could n't breathe under there,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bittner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Wausau </LOCATION> said Friday. `` I'm lucky I had enough guys there to get me out.'' `` I was squashed. All I wanted was to get this thing off of me,'' he said. <PERSON> Bittner </PERSON>, 35, was working on a fence being erected Thursday at <ORGANIZATION> Wausau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> when a hook connecting a section of fence to a crane came loose and the section fell on him, the <ORGANIZATION> Marathon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported. The sheet of quarter-inch thick steel, roughly seven feet wide and 30 feet long piece, pinned <PERSON> Bittner </PERSON> on top of scrap metal, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pagel </PERSON>, safety director in the Marathon County Sheriff's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> Workers freed him before firefighters arrived, the fire department said. `` I was working with about four or five other guys. They lifted the corner of the plate and got me out,'' <PERSON> Bittner </PERSON> said. `` I'm just glad people were there to help,'' he said. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Wausau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Bittner </PERSON> was helping an outside crew putting up the fence when the accident happened. `` I just figured we were all ... lucky that he did n't even have a broken bone,'' <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bittner </PERSON>, who was wearing a welding helmet when the fence section fell, was treated for minor injuries to his head