<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, July 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LIFE ABROAD: New Delhi's Monsoon _ A Time for Rejoicing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf ``The rains ... people dead,'' to update,
showing monsoon death toll at 370.</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 This is one of a series of periodic reports by <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> correspondents on people, places and things in other countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI,India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the dusty days of summer, when temperatures hover above 100 degrees for days on end, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> rejoices at the coming of the monsoon and its cooling rains. `` In the West, the rains are depressing. In <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> they are a time of great joy, release, beauty and romance,'' says <PERSON> Khushwant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a noted author and journalist. As the rains come, the dust settles. Parched gardens suddenly turn green. Temperatures come soothingly down and so do tempers. But the monsoon has its sad side. The rains that started early in July ended two years of drought in northern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, promising good crops at last, but they also unleashed floods that three weeks later had left at least 370 people dead around the country of drowning or disease spread by contaminated water. The death toll in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> from contaminated water approached 100. A city official said more than 7,100 others had been treated in hospitals for cholera or gastroenteritis. For <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, the downpour broke the stifling heat, but telephones went dead, potholes multiplied or grew deeper, and disease became a danger as tainted water seeped into pipes and wells. At the first delicious moment of the monsoon, though, the nourishing rain kept such troubles distant. `` The monsoon ... for most Indians ... is not only the source of life, but also their most exciting contact with nature,'' says author-journalist <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>. When the clouds first burst open over <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, dozens of half-naked children danced gleefully in the downpour and splashed in puddles in one impoverished neighborhood along the <LOCATION> Yamuna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. `` It's always like this,'' said <PERSON> Gulab </PERSON>, an elderly woman watching the fun. `` The children love to play in the rain, but they invariably get sick.'' More than 5,300 people have been treated this year for gastro-enteritis and cholera in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. At least 75 have died, most of them children. <PERSON> Maya </PERSON> <PERSON> Rao </PERSON>, a university teacher who has lived in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> for many years, described <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>'s monsoon this way: `` There is muck and mud all over, mosquitoes attack you in hordes, diseases spread like vice. It's impossible to get to places on time, given the state of the roads, and calling people on the phone is such a nuisance _ half the phones are dead.'' Then, she added, there's the humidity. `` The moment the rain stops, you sweat to death.'' Even so, Ms. <PERSON> Rao </PERSON> went on, she ca n't imagine life without the monsoon. `` What could be more delightful than eating ` bhutta' -LRB- roasted corn-on-the-cob -RRB- on your terrace as the grey-purple skies melt into rain?'' One city official, who insisted on anonymity, said he could do no work during the monsoon. `` It's too beautiful just to relax, sit and watch the rain,'' he said, as he sat watching the rain stream down his office window.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs July 29</NOTE>
