<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug. 5-7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bill Kirchenbauer Went From Class Clown to Standup Comic</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With his name and a birthplace like <LOCATION> Salzburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, you might expect comedian <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirchenbauer </PERSON> to talk like <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarzenegger </PERSON>. On request, <PERSON> Kirchenbauer </PERSON> does a pretty fair <PERSON> Schwarzenegger </PERSON>, but his otherwise unaccented speech reflects his peripatetic upbringing as an Army brat. `` I went to 13 schools in 12 years,'' he said. `` In just one year I went to four schools. I was always the new kid. I was also the class clown. They ca n't get mad at you if you're funny.'' <PERSON> Kirchenbauer </PERSON> is still funny, both as a standup comedian and as the star of the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> comedy show `` Just the 10 of Us.'' The show, a spinoff of `` Growing Pains,'' made its debut in the spring and will return in the fall. He had originally auditioned for another role on `` Growing Pains,'' which he did n't get. But they liked him so much they offered him the role of Coach. He plays Coach <PERSON> Lubbock </PERSON>, who loses his job at <ORGANIZATION> Dewey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> on `` Growing Pains'' and is forced to uproot his large family and take a new job at an all-boys prep school in a small town. He and his wife, played by <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, have five daughters, two sons, and one child on the way. `` Coach <PERSON> Lubbock </PERSON> was probably named after the city in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Kirchenbauer </PERSON>. `` I lived there, too, when <PERSON> Dad </PERSON> was in the Army. I was born in <LOCATION> Salzburg </LOCATION>, then I lived just about everywhere, from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. I think that had a lot to do with my becoming a standup comedian. I moved so much I became the class clown to get along. I began to look at each class as an audience. I said if you squint it does look like an audience. `` My father was a sergeant-major, although he's now retired. The first place I can remember was <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Benning </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>. We lived on <LOCATION> Ingersol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Loop </LOCATION> My mother called me <PERSON> Billiker </PERSON> <PERSON> Boop </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Ingersol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Loop </LOCATION>. I've never been in the Army myself. I do n't take orders very well, except from a director.'' He said he had been an entertainer for as long as he could remember. `` When I was 5 I began working with puppets,'' he said. `` I always put on a show before Christmas. I had a <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> puppet my parents gave me. Then around 12 they started looking like dolls so I quit. `` In my teens I started doing impressions. I did shows at the American Legion and places like that. But doing impressions is very limited. All you can do is take people out of context. And so many people did impressions better than me. Then I began to do impressions of things. Like garbage trucks and typewriters and roller deodorant.'' He had a job selling video editing equipment, but about 10 years ago he quit and worked full-time as a comedian. <PERSON> Kirchenbauer </PERSON> had previously worked with <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Thicke </PERSON> when he produced `` Fernwood 2-Night'' and `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> 2-Night.'' <PERSON> Kirchenbauer </PERSON> played egotistical singer <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Roletti </PERSON>. He said he sees Coach as a man who's idealistic about the way he raises his family. `` He just wants the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream for them,'' he said. `` My wife says he's like me: a bossy know-it-all, but a sweet kind of guy who would return a wallet if he found it.'' <PERSON> Kirchenbauer </PERSON> said the thing he likes most about the show is that he does n't have to travel as much. `` I enjoy doing the standup, but the travel gets you down,'' he said. `` Some people get rowdy in the clubs. I had to knock out a guy in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. I was using a big flashlight in my act and I hit him over the head with it. People think it's a game. You yell at the comedian and he yells back at you.'' <PERSON> Kirchenbauer </PERSON> has been appearing on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Tonight Show'' for eight years. The first time he was asked to be on the show he turned it down. He'd won a competition in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> for standup comics and he got the call after his picture ran in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Times. His manager told him he should n't go on `` The Tonight Show'' on a gimmick. `` I played the coach for six weeks on ` Just the 10 of Us' and now people think that's all I can do,'' he said. `` I've been doing comedy for more than 10 years.''
</TEXT>
