<HEAD>Banks Weathering Drought Well</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Major farm-lending banks are weathering the drought of the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and South remarkably well. The big debt-rating services say the protracted drought conditions that have dried up the profits of some farmers have left virtually no wrinkles on the quality of these banks' credit. The reason: Savvy bankers left nothing to chance following the farm crisis of the early 1980s. Most already had reduced their exposure to agriculture loans by paring down their portfolios and increasing reserves to cover possible losses, noted recent studies by <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The previous farm crisis also weeded out inefficient and highly indebted operations, while those that remained emerged stronger, more disciplined, with the help of farm insurance and government intervention, including price supports and disaster relief, the reports said. `` If anyone is feeling any pain it's likely to be smaller, unrated institutions,'' which normally do n't rely on the credit markets for additional capital, said <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s analyst and co-author of its drought-bank report. Both S & amp; P and <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s recently reaffirmed the credit ratings of bank holding companies with the largest exposures to agriculture loans, since the possibility of a drought or other problems already had been factored into their ratings. But they warned that if the same hot, dry weather conditions persisted next year, credit quality could suffer. A good credit rating translates into cheaper borrowing costs in the public sector. `` Their -LRB- banks' -RRB- access to the credit market helps them on an ongoing basis to expand in a diversified and less expensive manner,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroker </PERSON>, co-author of <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P's report. These days, credit raters are more concerned with broader problems facing banks, such as their exposure to loans to less developed countries and for real estate, Ms. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said. Banks with over 50 percent of their equity tied up in farm loans are most vulnerable, although only a handful of institutions fall into that category, according to S & amp; <ORGANIZATION> P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amarillo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bancorp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, whose senior debt has been rated non-investment grade, had the biggest exposure in relationship to its size, with its $ 167 million in agriculture loans representing a whopping 871 percent of its equity, <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P said. The banks with the largest overall farm-loan exposure, according to S & amp; P, were the large Western banks: <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which has about $ 950 million in agriculture loans; <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, $ 850 million; <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, $ 630 million; and <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bancorp </ORGANIZATION>, $ 596 million. <ORGANIZATION> Norwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, with $ 440 million in loans, is the largest agriculture lender in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. All of these big banks' loans are manageable because they represent under a third of their equity base, <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P said.
</TEXT>
