<HEAD>Orange Juice Squeeze Coming To An End</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An ADD containing weekly commodity price trends will follow
later in the cycle.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The orange juice supply squeeze that has raised retail prices and propelled futures prices to record highs should ease next month as shipments of frozen concentrate from <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> resume, experts say. But consumers may not see a drop in retail prices of frozen concentrate until next year, after the new <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> orange crop has been harvested and processed. `` Once we get into the end of the year you get concerns about <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> freezes, so it might be a while before consumers begin to see orange juice prices fall,'' said <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON>, orange juice market analyst for the New York-based investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` We're not looking for a substantial break to occur until the end of the winter,'' she said. Although <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports of frozen Brazilian juice have declined steadily as <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s citrus groves have recovered from a string of freezes in the early 1980s, imports from <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> still account for about 40 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumption, Ms. <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> says it exported the frozen equivalent of about 77 million gallons of orange juice to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from last July through this past May, about 40 percent less than in the same period a year ago. The declining <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dependence on Brazilian imports has been offset to some degree by rising Brazilian exports to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> virtually sold out of orange juice during its latest July-June marketing year. The new <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> orange crop wo n't be ready for processing until late fall or early winter. So <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> orange juice packers, caught between two harvests, were forced to dig deeper into their frozen stocks and raise their prices. Processing of the rapidly maturing new Brazilian crop will begin in two weeks or so, and shipments to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should resume before the end of August, analysts said. The resumption of imports should bring down prices for future delivery of frozen concentrated orange juice, which rose to a record $ 2.04 a pound July 18 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Orange juice for September delivery settled Friday at about $ 1.88 a pound. Wholesale orange juice prices generally lag behind futures prices by two or three months, Ms. <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON> said. So retailers, who are now paying about $ 1.65 a pound for frozen concentrated orange juice compared with about $ 1.30 a pound a year ago, may see even higher prices this fall. Consumers may not see significantly lower prices until next year, but competition among producers and retailers may keep a lid on prices at the retail level, she said.
