<HEAD>Oil Prices Little Changed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Energy futures prices were little changed after falling in early trading and then recovering on technical factors. The September contract for the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, fell 1 cent to $ 16.38 a 42-gallon barrel Friday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. On Thursday, the contract rose 34 cents. Among refined products traded on the exchange, the contract for August delivery of unleaded gasoline slipped 0.03 cent to 52.07 cents a gallon, while August home heating oil fell 0.58 cent to 44.95 cents a gallon. `` It was a mixed-bag session,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Azarow </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Early trading was dominated by events in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Azarow </PERSON> said. Traders became pessimistic about the impact the proposed cease-fire between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> could have on already abundant world oil supplies, <PERSON> Azarow </PERSON> said. Both countries could step up oil production, adding to the glut, as they try to repair their economies following the war, he said. Traders were thinking, `` Maybe the outbreak of peace is not that good for prices after all,'' <PERSON> Azarow </PERSON> said. Contracts then fell to their lows _ with the September <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate contract sinking to $ 16.12 _ after reports of an Iraqi attack on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Azarow </PERSON> said. But when prices did not fall further, the session turned around on technical factors, <PERSON> Azarow </PERSON> said. `` New buyers felt confident because the market showed some support,'' he said.
</TEXT>
