<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Prices Up 0.3 Percent in June; Wall Street Finishes Down
Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market failed to shake its recent slump despite an encouraging government report that consumer prices rose a modest 0.3 percent in June. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 25.60 points Friday to 2,060.99, stretching its loss for the week to 68.46 points. That marked the biggest weekly decline for the closely watched average since it dropped 76.26 points April 11-15. Despite the favorable consumer price report and a modest decline in interest rates, investors still showed little enthusiasm for stocks, analysts said. In another dose of good economic news, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said a surge in quarterly income tax payments by companies and individuals gave the federal government a rare $ 9.5 billion surplus in June. That left the cumulative red ink for the first nine months of the fiscal year below last year's levels. On the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, uncertainty about the weather outlook for the weekend and beyond in the drought-parched Farm Belt pushed most crop futures prices lower. Soybean prices for near-term delivery fell for the fifth straight day, bringing the August contract to just over $ 8.30 a bushel, the lowest price for near-month delivery since June 2. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report said the 0.3 percent June rise in consumer prices worked out to a moderate annual rate of 4.2 percent, with the effects of the drought showing up clearly only in poultry and egg prices. Food price rises held to a 0.6 percent gain despite the biggest surge in poultry and egg prices since August 1986, when the nation was in the midst of another drought. Offsetting increases on grocery shelves were a 0.2 percent decline in energy prices and a 0.3 percent drop in clothing costs. `` I'd say the report is good news. It clearly shows that inflation is not getting out of hand. It has accelerated over the last year or so, but very gradually and very unevenly,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Chimerine </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, forecasting firm.
</TEXT>
